eshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mayse","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Mayes  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mayes","meanings":["English: variant of   May   1, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":29,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":38,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":49,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":65,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":67,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":100,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Henry Mayse was born in 1520, in Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England. He married Margaret Woodborne on 16 November 1564, in Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1520–":"1520–Surnud","1535–1596":"1535–1596","1567–1620":"1567–1620","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","15